05202nam a22007815i 9781501730023DE-B159720191126113341.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191126s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017300237 a10.1515/97815017300232doi  a(DE-B1597)503484  a(OCoLC)1059282997  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aML3917.S65bT66 2006eb 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a780.6/0472231 aTomoff, Kiril, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCreative Union :bThe Professional Organization of Soviet Composers, 1939-1953 /cKiril Tomoff. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b12 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: The Professional Organization Of Soviet Composers -- t1. The Formation Of The Composers' Union, 1932-41 -- t2. Administering The Creative Process -- t3. Composers On The March, 1941-45 -- tPart II: Profession And Power, 1946-53 -- t4. Zhdanovshchina And The Ogolevets Affair -- t5. Brouhaha! Party Intervention And Professional Consolidation, 1948 -- t6. Anticosmopolitanism And The Music Profession, 1949-53 -- t7. The Results Of Party Intervention -- tPart III: Professionals And The Stalinist Cultural Elite -- t8. Muzfond, Royalties, And Popularity -- t9. Elite Hierarchies -- t10. "Most Respected Comrade...": Informal Networks In The Stalinist Music World -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy did the Stalin era, a period characterized by bureaucratic control and the reign of Socialist Realism in the arts, witness such an extraordinary upsurge of musical creativity and the prominence of musicians in the cultural elite? This is one of the questions that Kiril Tomoff seeks to answer in Creative Union, the first book about any of the professional unions that dominated Soviet cultural life at the time. Drawing on hitherto untapped archives, he shows how the Union of Soviet Composers established control over the music profession and negotiated the relationship between composers and the Communist Party leadership. Central to Tomoff's argument is the institutional authority and prestige that the musical profession accrued and deployed within Soviet society, enabling musicians to withstand the postwar disciplinary campaigns that were so crippling in other artistic and literary spheres.Most accounts of Soviet musical life focus on famous individuals or the campaign against Shostakovich's Lady Macbeth and Zhdanov's postwar attack on musical formalism. Tomoff's approach, while not downplaying these notorious events, shows that the Union was able to develop and direct a musical profession that enjoyed enormous social prestige. The Union's leadership was able to use its expertise to determine the criteria of musical value with a degree of independence. Tomoff's book reveals the complex and mutable interaction of creative intelligentsia and political elite in a period hitherto characterized as one of totalitarian control.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 0aMusic and statezSoviet Union. 0aMusiczSoviet UnionxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiciansxLabor unionszSoviet Union. 4aLabor History. 4aMusical Arts & Ethnomusicology. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2018z978311060655340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501730023zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501730023.jp